'''Deborah Margaret Lavin''', [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]]<ref name="DE">{{Cite web|url=https://www.debretts.com/|title=Debrett's homepage - The trusted source on British social skills, etiquette and style|website=Debrett's|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> (born 22 September 1939) is a [[South Africa]]n academic and [[historian]], resident in the [[United Kingdom]] for most of her career.
==Early life== Lavin was born on 22 September 1939.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> She attended [[Rhodes University]], [[South Africa]] and [[Lady Margaret Hall]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], graduating in 1961.
==Academic career== Lavin has lectured at the [[University of Witwatersrand]] as well as [[Queen's University Belfast]] and was a Senior Associate of [[St Antony's College, Oxford]].<ref name="trevs">Martin, Susan TREVS A Celebration of 40 years of Trevelyan College Durham.</ref> In 1980 she relocated to [[University of Durham|Durham]] where she was co-director of the Research Institute for the Study of Change<ref name="the">{{Cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=95710&sectioncode=26|title=Appointments|date=1995-10-20|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-01-11|language=en}}</ref> and a lecturer in the Department of Modern History, as well as Principal of [[Trevelyan College]] from 1979–1995.<ref name="trevs"/> She was President of the Howlands Trust and from 1995 to 1997<ref name="DE"/> was Principal-elect of the new [[Colleges of the University of Durham|College]] to be developed at the Howlands Farm, which eventually became [[Josephine Butler College]].
==Bibliography== *''South African Memories: Scraps of History'', Ad. Donker, 1979 (co-author)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allbookstores.com/author/Deborah_Lavin.html|title=Deborah Lavin Books - List of books by Deborah Lavin|website=www.allbookstores.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> *''From Empire to International Commonwealth: A Biography of [[Lionel Curtis]]'', Oxford, 1995<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.books-by-isbn.com/authors/deborah/lavin/|title=✎ Books by Deborah Lavin|website=www.books-by-isbn.com|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> *''The Condominium Remembered:Proceedings of the Durham Sudan Historical Records Conference 1982'', University of Durham, Centre for Middle Easte, 1993 <ref>http://dro.dur.ac.uk/133/</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://openlibrary.org/books/OL8289028M/The_Condominium_Remembered|title=The Condominium Remembered (1991 edition)|last=OpenLibrary.org|website=Open Library|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref>
