[[File:Atlas Forge - geograph.org.uk - 404186.jpg|thumb|right|The Atlas Forge rolling mill]] '''Thomas Walmsley and Sons''' was a company that manufactured [[wrought iron]]. It was founded in 1866 or 1869 by Thomas Walmsley at the Atlas Forge on a site bounded by Bridgeman Street and Fletcher Street in [[Bolton]], then in Lancashire, England. The forge had at least 16 [[Puddling (metallurgy)|puddling]] furnaces and forging and rolling mills.<ref name = "TownleyP56" >{{Harvp|Townley|1995|p=56}}</ref>
In 1874 a [[Rastrick boiler]] at the forge [[boiler explosion|exploded]], causing six fatalities.<ref name="McEwen, Atlas Forge" >{{Cite book |title=Historic Steam Boiler Explosions |first=Alan |last=McEwen |year=2009 |publisher=Sledgehammer |isbn=978-0-9532725-2-5 |ref=harv |pages=8–11 }}</ref>
Production lasted for more than 100 years until 1975 when it was the last plant in the United Kingdom to produce wrought iron. Much of the plant, the wrought iron rolling mill, the Rastrick boiler and the steam engine that powered it were preserved in working order by the [[Ironbridge Gorge Museum Trust]] for its [[Blists Hill Victorian Town#Ironworks area|Blists Hill]] museum where it is used to demonstrate the process to visitors.<ref name = "TownleyP56" /><ref>{{citation |title=Highlights |url=http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/collections/highlights/ |publisher=Ironbridge Gorge Museums |accessdate=29 March 2012 }}</ref> A [[steam hammer]] supplied to the company by [[Nasmyth, Gaskell and Company|Nasmyth & Wilson]] of Patricroft is preserved outside [[Bolton University]].<ref>{{citation |title=Heritage steam hammer moves home|url=http://www.bolton.ac.uk/News/News-Articles/2009/nov-2009-5.aspx |publisher=Bolton University |accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref>
[[File:Atlas Forge, Bridgeman Street, Bolton - geograph.org.uk - 404170.jpg|thumb|Atlas Forge and the figure of [[Atlas (mythology)|Atlas]], as steel stockholders in 1983]] After 1975 the company became steel stockholders as 'Walmsley Steelstock' and closed in 1984.
==Walmsley family== Thomas Walmsley was born in 1812, was an iron agent and tinplate worker in 1845 in Oxford Street Bolton. In 1869 he was an agent for the Grosmont [[pig iron]] and [[Bowling Iron Company]] from the Phoenix Ironworks in Crook Street. He had set up his own iron works by 1869.<ref name = "TownleyP56" /> He was Mayor of Bolton from 1869 to 1871.<ref>{{citation |title=Thomas Walmsley|url=http://www.boltonsmayors.org.uk/walmsley-t.html |publisher=Bolton Council|accessdate=29 March 2012 }}</ref> He died in 1890 and the business passed to his son, Richard and subsequently to Richard's sons, Reginald and Ernest.<ref name = "TownleyP56" />
